concept_explanation.predicate:
**`Predicate<T>`** — a function that takes a T and returns boolean.

```java
import java.util.function.Predicate;

Predicate<String> isLong    = s -> s.length() > 5;
Predicate<Integer> isEven   = n -> n % 2 == 0;
Predicate<Product> expensive = p -> p.getPrice() > 1000;
```

Key method: `boolean test(T t)`

**Using Predicates:**
```java
System.out.println(isLong.test("Hello"));         // false
System.out.println(isLong.test("Hyderabad"));     // true

// With List.removeIf (which takes Predicate<E>):
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("Raj", "Aisha", "Priya"));
names.removeIf(isLong);   // removes strings longer than 5
// names is now [Raj]
```

**Composing predicates:**
```java
Predicate<Integer> isEven     = n -> n % 2 == 0;
Predicate<Integer> isPositive = n -> n > 0;

Predicate<Integer> evenAndPositive = isEven.and(isPositive);
Predicate<Integer> evenOrNegative  = isEven.or(isPositive.negate());
Predicate<Integer> notEven         = isEven.negate();

System.out.println(evenAndPositive.test(4));   // true
System.out.println(evenAndPositive.test(-4));  // false
System.out.println(notEven.test(3));           // true
```

`and()`, `or()`, `negate()` return new Predicates — composable without creating new lambdas.

concept_explanation.function:
**`Function<T, R>`** — takes a T, returns an R. Transforms one type to another.

```java
import java.util.function.Function;

Function<String, Integer> length    = s -> s.length();
Function<String, String>  upperCase = s -> s.toUpperCase();
Function<Product, Double> getPrice  = p -> p.getPrice();
Function<String, Integer> parseInt  = Integer::parseInt;  // method reference
```

Key method: `R apply(T t)`

**Using Functions:**
```java
System.out.println(length.apply("Hello"));        // 5
System.out.println(upperCase.apply("hyderabad")); // HYDERABAD

List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj");
// map is not a List method — it's Stream (Topic 8.3)
// but we can simulate:
List<String> upper = new ArrayList<>();
names.forEach(name -> upper.add(upperCase.apply(name)));
// upper = [AISHA, RAJ]
```

**Composing functions with `andThen()`:**
```java
Function<String, String> trim    = s -> s.trim();
Function<String, String> upper   = s -> s.toUpperCase();
Function<String, Integer> length = s -> s.length();

Function<String, String>  trimThenUpper  = trim.andThen(upper);
Function<String, Integer> trimThenLength = trim.andThen(length);

System.out.println(trimThenUpper.apply("  hello  "));   // HELLO
System.out.println(trimThenLength.apply("  hello  "));  // 5
```

`andThen(after)` returns a new Function that first applies `this`, then applies `after`.

concept_explanation.consumer:
**`Consumer<T>`** — takes a T, returns nothing (void). Performs a side effect.

```java
import java.util.function.Consumer;

Consumer<String> print     = s -> System.out.println(s);
Consumer<Product> save     = p -> database.save(p);
Consumer<String> log       = s -> logger.info(s);
```

Key method: `void accept(T t)`

**Using Consumers:**
```java
print.accept("Hello");  // prints 'Hello'

List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj");
names.forEach(print);  // forEach takes Consumer<T>
// prints Aisha, then Raj
```

**Composing consumers with `andThen()`:**
```java
Consumer<String> printUpper = s -> System.out.println(s.toUpperCase());
Consumer<String> printLen   = s -> System.out.println("Length: " + s.length());

Consumer<String> both = printUpper.andThen(printLen);
both.accept("hello");
// Prints:
// HELLO
// Length: 5
```

`Consumer.andThen()` runs both consumers in sequence.

**`BiConsumer<T, U>`** — takes two arguments:
```java
BiConsumer<String, Integer> printScore = (name, score) -> 
    System.out.println(name + ": " + score);

// Map.forEach takes BiConsumer<K, V>:
scores.forEach(printScore);
// OR:
scores.forEach((name, score) -> System.out.println(name + ": " + score));
```

concept_explanation.supplier:
**`Supplier<T>`** — takes nothing, returns a T. Produces a value lazily.

```java
import java.util.function.Supplier;

Supplier<String> greeting  = () -> "Hello, World!";
Supplier<Double> random    = () -> Math.random();
Supplier<List<String>> newList = () -> new ArrayList<>();
Supplier<LocalDate> today  = LocalDate::now;  // method reference
```

Key method: `T get()`

**Using Suppliers:**
```java
System.out.println(greeting.get());  // Hello, World!
System.out.println(random.get());    // random number

// Lazy default — only compute if needed:
public User getUser(int id, Supplier<User> defaultUser) {
    User u = cache.get(id);
    return u != null ? u : defaultUser.get();  // only calls defaultUser if not cached
}
```

**Why Supplier?** It defers execution. The lambda body doesn't run until `.get()` is called. Useful for:
- Lazy default values (avoid expensive computation if not needed)
- Object factories (`ArrayList::new`)
- Test data generation
- Logging messages that are only computed if log level is enabled

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
import java.util.function.*;
import java.util.*;

class DataPipeline<T> {
    private Predicate<T> filter = t -> true;      // default: keep all
    private UnaryOperator<T> transform = t -> t;  // default: identity (no change)
    private Consumer<T> output = t -> {};          // default: do nothing

    public DataPipeline<T> filter(Predicate<T> p) {
        this.filter = p;
        return this;  // fluent builder
    }

    public DataPipeline<T> transform(UnaryOperator<T> op) {
        this.transform = op;
        return this;
    }

    public DataPipeline<T> output(Consumer<T> c) {
        this.output = c;
        return this;
    }

    public void process(List<T> data) {
        for (T item : data) {
            if (filter.test(item)) {          // Predicate
                T result = transform.apply(item);  // UnaryOperator
                output.accept(result);             // Consumer
            }
        }
    }
}
```

```java
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8);
List<Integer> results = new ArrayList<>();

new DataPipeline<Integer>()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)               // Predicate: even
    .transform(n -> n * 2)                 // UnaryOperator: double
    .output(n -> results.add(n))           // Consumer: collect
    .process(nums);

System.out.println("Doubled evens: " + results);
```

Evens: 2, 4, 6, 8. Doubled: 4, 8, 12, 16.

worked_example.final_code:
import java.util.*;
import java.util.function.*;

class DataPipeline<T> {
    private Predicate<T>    filter    = t -> true;
    private UnaryOperator<T> transform = t -> t;
    private Consumer<T>     output    = t -> {};

    DataPipeline<T> filter(Predicate<T> p)     { this.filter = p; return this; }
    DataPipeline<T> transform(UnaryOperator<T> op) { this.transform = op; return this; }
    DataPipeline<T> output(Consumer<T> c)       { this.output = c; return this; }

    void process(List<T> data) {
        for (T item : data) {
            if (filter.test(item))
                output.accept(transform.apply(item));
        }
    }
}

public class FunctionalPipeline {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> cities = Arrays.asList("Delhi", "Hyderabad", "Mumbai", "Bengaluru", "Pune");

        System.out.println("Cities longer than 5 chars (UPPERCASE):");
        new DataPipeline<String>()
            .filter(s -> s.length() > 5)
            .transform(s -> s.toUpperCase())
            .output(System.out::println)  // method reference!
            .process(cities);

        System.out.println("\nDoubled even numbers:");
        List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8);
        List<Integer> results = new ArrayList<>();
        new DataPipeline<Integer>()
            .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
            .transform(n -> n * 2)
            .output(results::add)  // method reference on instance!
            .process(nums);
        System.out.println(results);
    }
}
